FINANCE - Aid. Cruts, Chairman (Wisbrock, Huels, Jokerst)
• July 31, 2023, Monthly Financial Report. Alderman Cruts summarized the monthly financial report.

• Consideration of proposed amendments to the City's Financial Policy. In August, the Board continued this matter to September to allow the Board additional time for review and provide Staff additional time to finalize revisions to Section 700 - Capital Assets.

Financial Consultant Tammy Alsop gave an overview of the newly amended Section 700 - Capital Assets, which was available for review and consideration in conjunction with the overall amended Financial Policy provided to the Board in August. Changes from the previous Section 700 include the deletion of "Leased Assets" (as they are no longer defined as an asset) and the addition of procedures.

Alderman Cruts made a motion to forward to the September Board of Aldermen meeting the proposed amendments to the City's Financial Policy. The motion was seconded by Alderman Wisbrock. Upon a voice vote being taken, the motion passed unanimously by the Committee.

• Consideration of the 2023 Mid-Year Budget Amendment. Financial Consultant Tammy Alsop gave an overview of the 2023 mid-year budget amendments.

Following discussion, Alderman Cruts made a motion to forward to the September Board of Aldermen meeting the 2023 Mid-Year Budget Amendment. The motion was seconded by Alderman Jokerst. Upon a voice vote being taken, the motion passed unanimously by the Committee.

• Consideration of an amended Long Term Capital Plan (2023-2027). Financial Consultant Tammy Alsop gave an overview of the amended long term capital plan.

Alderman Jokerst inquired when line item for soccer field lighting removal from the Capital Plan would be discussed. City Administrator Andrea N. Finkbiner replied consideration for removal can be part of 2024 budget discussions in November.

Following discussion, Alderman Cruts made a motion to forward to the September Board of Aldermen meeting the amended Long Term Capital Plan (2023-2027). The motion was seconded by Alderman Huels. Upon a voice vote being taken, the motion passed unanimously by the Committee.

PLANNING AND ZONING COMMISSION REPORT - Aid Harrell, Liaison
All recommendations from the Planning and Zoning Commission will be forwarded to the next Board Meeting for approval unless otherwise noted.
• Announcements for the Planning and Zoning Commission Meeting:
• The Planning and Zoning Commission will hold a workshop regarding amendments to the Comprehensive Development Plan in advance of the October 3 meeting at 6:00 p.m.

• The Planning and Zoning Commission will hold their annual training in advance of the November 7 meeting at 6:00 p.m.

• The Planning and Zoning Commission recommended the following:

■ Approval, with conditions, of CASE 2023-SUP-11: A Petition by Corbin Holtzman on behalf of Talaria MO, LLC for a Special Use Permit to operate a Marijuana Transportation Facility at 2275 Cassens Drive, Suite 130. The parcel is addressed as 143 Cassens Court and is zoned "IP-1" Industrial Park District.

Conditions of Approval:
1. This Special Use Permit approval is solely for Talaria MO, LLC to operate a Marijuana Transportation Facility at 2275 Cassens Drive, Suite 130, in accordance with Chapter 430, Article IX of the Zoning Code. Said use does not include laboratory testing or certifying of Marijuana.

2. Proof of State Licensing, as required under Section 430.680 of the Zoning Code, must be provided to the Community Development Director before an Occupancy Permit is issued for the subject location.

3. Proposed interior renovations to the subject location will require a separate Building Permit. 4. Compliance with all other applicable codes and ordinances of the City of Fenton.

Alderman Harrell shared this Case was continued from the August Planning and Zoning meeting to address the Commissions concerns. At the September meeting, it was confirmed by the applicant that this facility will not be a testing facility, will not have a lab, and is not a storage facility, but product may be temporarily held on-site within a secure room when deliveries cannot be made within a workday, but state requirements do not allow product to be held for more than 72 hours.

Petitioner Michelle Morris was in attendance at the meeting via Zoom Videoconference and had nothing further to add.

• Approval, with conditions, of CASE 2023-SUP-12: A Petition by Abier Mseitef of S&H Spirit, Inc. d/b/a Fenton Liquor and Tobacco for a Special Use Permit to operate a Liquor Store and Tobacco Shop at 645 Gravois Road. The property is zoned "OT-2" Olde Towne District.

Conditions of Approval:
1. Approval of the Special Use Permit is for S&H Spirit, Inc. d/b/a Fenton Liquor and Tobacco to operate a Liquor Store at 645 Gravois Road, as indicated on the plans provided with the application and dated July 25, 2023.
2. Compliance with all other applicable City Codes and Ordinances.

Alderman Harrell explained that a SUP was approved in April for Stars Liquor and Tobacco; however, the Petitioner recently established a new corporate entity and business name. Additionally, the Board approved a text amendment in May to add Tobacco Shops to the Code as a Use that now requires a SUP in "OT-2". Since SUPs are non-transferable, and a SUP is now needed for Tobacco Shops, the Petitioner is seeking a new SUP. No changes to the operation of the business are proposed.

City Attorney Erin Seele noted there was a typo in conditions of approval, and it will also include operating as a Tobacco Shop.

• Approval, with conditions, of CASE 2023-SUP-13: A Petition by Land R Group Corp. for a Special Use Permit to operate an Indoor Limited Recreational Facility at 2045 Ritzert Court. The property is zoned "IP-1" Industrial Park District.

Conditions of Approval:
1. This Special Use Permit is solely for Land R Group Corp to operate an Indoor Limited Recreational Facility at 2045 Ritzert Court.

2. Minimally, an Occupancy Permit will be required before the building is occupied.

3. A separate Municipal Zoning Approval (MZA) by the City of Fenton for any proposed interior remodel or proposed signage will be required. 4. Compliance with all other applicable City Codes and Ordinances.

Alderman Harrell explained the facility will be a basketball training franchise, offering virtual interactive training technology, skills training, and one on one or small group training with former professional basketball players.

Alderman Harrell noted that at the Commission meeting, in response to questions about available parking, it was stated that they only anticipate twelve to fifteen (12-15) kids at one time with most being dropped off. Additionally, the hours will vary based on the season, with winter hours between 2:00 p.m.- 9:00 p.m. and extended summer hours between 10:00 a.m.- 9:00 p.m.

Petitioner Rob Powers was in attendance at the meeting via Zoom Videoconference and had nothing further to add.

There were no questions or comments.

• Other items from the Planning and Zoning Department: There were no items for discussion.

PARKS AND RECREATION COMMITTEE - Aid Huels, Liaison
All recommendations from the Parks and Recreation Committee will be forwarded to the next Board Meeting for approval unless otherwise noted.
• Announcements from the Parks and Recreation Committee meeting:
• A motion approved for Staff to obtain quotes for two to four (2-4) Pickleball Courts in Fenton City Park, constructed with standard pickleball court materials and with needed fencing, nets, etc. for further consideration.

Alderman Jokerst suggested considering courts to be dual purpose tennis court and pickleball court. Alderman Maserang inquired if other locations in the City have been considered to have courts out of the floodplain.

Public Works Director Dan Howard shared he is in the process of obtaining quotes and locations can be discussed further at the next Parks and Recreation Committee meeting.

• Discussion regarding parks and recreation projects for the 2024 Fiscal Year Budget was continued to the October meeting.

• The Parks and Recreation Committee recommended the following:
• Approval of new informational signs in City Parks as proposed by Piros Signs under Option A.1 and with Piros providing the installation.

Alderman Jokerst suggested removing redundancy of parking rules.

City Administrator Andrea N. Finkbiner shared park hours will be in a larger font, speed limit will be in a smaller font and can remove redundancy of parking rules.

There was discussion of the high expense of $17,000 for signs/posts/installation by Piros. Public Works Director Dan Howard shared the Public Works Department can perform the installation however it may not be until later in the year as time allows. He noted the Parks and Recreation Committee recommended Piros to expedite installation.

City Administrator Andrea N. Finkbiner shared she could try to negotiate a better price for posts to reduce cost or have the City purchase the posts directly.

Alderman Clauss and Alderman Wisbrock expressed they were in favor of Public Works Department performing the installation. Mayor Maurath shared he was in favor of Public Works Department performing the installation and suggested authorizing overtime hours to have Staff install on weekends.

Alderman Huels made a motion to approve Piros Signs under A.1 and have Public Works Department install the signs. The motion was seconded by Alderman Clauss. Upon a voice vote being taken, the motion passed unanimously by the Board of Aldermen.

